## TEST STRUCTURE

When writing tests:

1. ORGANIZE tests following this structure:
   - Place unit tests in the same file as the code (using `#[cfg(test)]`)
   - Use the `tests/` directory for integration tests
   - Group tests logically by functionality
   - Name tests descriptively

2. FOLLOW the Arrange-Act-Assert pattern:
   - ARRANGE: Set up test data and conditions
   - ACT: Execute the code being tested
   - ASSERT: Verify the results match expectations

3. WRITE self-contained tests:
   - Tests should not depend on other tests
   - Each test should clean up after itself
   - Use setup and teardown helpers for common code
   - Avoid global state where possible

ONE SOLUTION ONLY:
```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;
    
    // Helper function for common setup
    fn create_test_data() -> TestData {
        // Create and return test data
        TestData::new(/* parameters */)
    }
    
    #[test]
    fn test_process_simple_case() {
        // Arrange
        let data = create_test_data();
        let processor = Processor::new();
        
        // Act
        let result = processor.process(&data);
        
        // Assert
        assert!(result.is_ok());
        assert_eq!(result.unwrap().value, 42);
    }
    
    #[test]
    fn test_process_error_handling() {
        // Arrange
        let invalid_data = TestData::new_invalid();
        let processor = Processor::new();
        
        // Act
        let result = processor.process(&invalid_data);
        
        // Assert
        assert!(result.is_err());
        assert_eq!(result.unwrap_err().to_string(), "Invalid data");
    }
}
```

