## TESTING TOOLS

Use these testing tools for different scenarios:

1. USE Rust's built-in testing framework for unit tests:
   - `#[test]` attribute for test functions
   - `assert!`, `assert_eq!`, `assert_ne!` macros
   - `#[should_panic]` for tests that should fail
   - `cargo test` to run tests

2. USE specialized testing tools when appropriate:
   - Proptest for property-based testing
   - Criterion for benchmarking
   - Mockall for mocking dependencies
   - Insta for snapshot testing

3. IMPLEMENT custom testing utilities when needed:
   - Test harnesses for complex setups
   - Comparison helpers for domain-specific types
   - Test data generators
   - Visual comparison tools

ONE SOLUTION ONLY:
```rust
// Property-based testing example
#[cfg(test)]
mod property_tests {
    use super::*;
    use proptest::prelude::*;
    
    proptest! {
        #[test]
        fn test_reconstruction_preserves_dimensions(
            width in 10u32..100,
            height in 10u32..100,
            depth in 10u32..100
        ) {
            // Arrange
            let volume = create_test_volume(width, height, depth);
            let reconstructor = Reconstructor::new();
            
            // Act
            let result = reconstructor.process(&volume)?;
            
            // Assert
            prop_assert_eq!(result.width, width);
            prop_assert_eq!(result.height, height);
            prop_assert_eq!(result.depth, depth);
        }
    }
}

// Benchmark example
#[cfg(test)]
mod benchmarks {
    use super::*;
    use criterion::{black_box, criterion_group, criterion_main, Criterion};
    
    fn bench_reconstruction(c: &mut Criterion) {
        let data = create_benchmark_data();
        let reconstructor = Reconstructor::new();
        
        c.bench_function("reconstruct_volume", |b| {
            b.iter(|| reconstructor.process(black_box(&data)))
        });
    }
    
    criterion_group!(benches, bench_reconstruction);
    criterion_main!(benches);
}
```

