## MOCK TESTING

For testing components with dependencies:

1. PREFER real implementations where feasible:
   - Use actual implementations for simple dependencies
   - Create lightweight in-memory versions where appropriate
   - Only mock complex or external dependencies

2. IMPLEMENT mocks correctly:
   - Mock at interface boundaries (traits)
   - Only mock what you need to control
   - Make mocks behave realistically
   - Document mock behavior

3. STRUCTURE tests with mocks:
   - Set up mock expectations clearly
   - Verify interactions with mocks
   - Don't over-specify expectations
   - Focus on behavior, not implementation details

ONE SOLUTION ONLY:
```rust
// Mock testing example
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;
    use mockall::predicate::*;
    use mockall::*;
    
    // Create a mock for the DataProvider trait
    mock! {
        DataProvider {}
        
        trait DataProvider {
            fn get_data(&self, id: &str) -> Result<Data, Error>;
            fn save_data(&self, data: &Data) -> Result<(), Error>;
        }
    }
    
    #[test]
    fn test_processor_saves_transformed_data() {
        // Arrange
        let mut mock_provider = MockDataProvider::new();
        
        // Set up expectations
        let input_data = Data::new("test_content");
        let expected_output = Data::new("TRANSFORMED_test_content");
        
        mock_provider
            .expect_get_data()
            .with(eq("test_id"))
            .times(1)
            .returning(move |_| Ok(input_data.clone()));
            
        mock_provider
            .expect_save_data()
            .with(eq(expected_output.clone()))
            .times(1)
            .returning(|_| Ok(()));
        
        let processor = Processor::new(Box::new(mock_provider));
        
        // Act
        let result = processor.process_and_save("test_id");
        
        // Assert
        assert!(result.is_ok());
    }
}
```

